Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with a pinch of @salt{} for the @penne pasta{200%g}. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}. Halve the @mangetout{150%g} widthways. Finely chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}(chopped, stalks and all). Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Zest the @lemon{1/2}(zested and cut in half).

When boiling, pop the wheat pasta into the pan of water and cook for ~{10%minutes}. Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and return to the saucepan, off the heat. Drizzle over a little @oil{} and stir through (to stop it from sticking together!), then cover with a #lid{} to keep warm.

In the meantime, heat a glug of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} over medium heat. Once hot, add the onion and cook until soft and starting to colour, stirring occasionally, ~{5-8%minutes}. Once softened, stir in the mangetout, garlic and @ham hock{125%g}. Cook for ~{1%minute} more.

While the onion is cooking, mix the @creme fraiche{200%g}, @grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g}, @wholegrain mustard{1} and lemon zest together in a #small bowl{}.

Next, stir the crème fraîche mix into the frying pan. Add the @water{100%ml} and stir well to combine. Cook until thickened and reduced, then remove from the heat, ~{2-3%minutes}. Stir through the chopped parsley and season to taste with a pinch of @salt{}, a good grind of @black pepper{} and a squeeze of lemon juice.

As soon as you are happy with the flavour of the sauce, add the wheat pasta to the frying pan and gently toss to coat. Carefully reheat the wheat pasta if necessary and add a splash of water if the sauce is a little thick. Taste and add more salt, pepper and lemon juice if you feel it needs it. Divide between your bowls and dig in. Enjoy!